ADDITIONAL TERMS FOR JUSTICE SYSTEM FRAMEWORK

1. ETHICAL USE REQUIREMENT
   This software is designed to promote justice, protect victims, and improve
   the criminal justice system. Users must not employ this software for purposes
   that violate human rights, enable discrimination, or undermine due process.

2. TRANSPARENCY REQUIREMENT
   Any deployment of AI/ML components must maintain transparency in decision-making
   processes and provide mechanisms for human oversight and appeal.

3. PRIVACY PROTECTION
   Implementations must comply with applicable privacy laws (GDPR, HIPAA, etc.)
   and maintain constitutional protections for individuals.

4. VICTIM PROTECTION
   Systems must prioritize victim safety and rights, including protection of
   sensitive information and trauma-informed design.

5. OPEN SOURCE COMMITMENT
   Derivative works should remain open source to benefit the broader community,
   though this is encouraged rather than legally required under MIT license.

6. RESEARCH AND EVALUATION
   Users are encouraged to share outcomes, research findings, and lessons learned
   to advance the field of justice technology.

7. NO WARRANTY FOR LEGAL ADVICE
   This software does not constitute legal advice. Users should consult qualified
   legal professionals for specific legal matters.

8. COMPLIANCE WITH LAW
   Users must comply with all applicable federal, state, and local laws in their
   jurisdiction when deploying or using this software.
